No game rules in UI components. Plan API coupling changes per `workflow.mdc`.

## Purpose

Guide the Next.js 15 App Router frontend (`@draft-io/frontend`): server/client components, API integration, and UI patterns. The frontend is a **thin presentation layer** — it displays data and captures user intent; game rules and validation live on the backend.

## Required Behavior

### Project Structure

```
apps/frontend/src/
├── app/              # App Router pages, layouts, global styles
├── components/       # Reusable UI components (when added)
├── features/         # Feature-specific UI + hooks (when added)
└── lib/
    └── api/          # HTTP client, API helpers
```

### API Client

- All backend calls go through `lib/api/` — never scatter `fetch` across components.
- Base URL from `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL`, defaulting to `http://localhost:3001/api/v1`.
- Expect `ApiResponse<T>` envelope: access data via `response.data`.
- Throw typed errors (`ApiClientError`) with `statusCode` for error boundaries and toasts.

### Server vs Client Components

- Default to **Server Components** for data fetching and static layout.
- Add `'use client'` only when needed: interactivity, hooks, browser APIs, realtime.
- Fetch on the server when possible; pass serializable props to client children.

### Shared Types

- Import API types from `@draft-io/shared-types` — never redefine `PlayerSummary`, `ApiResponse`, etc.
- If a new API shape is needed, add it to `packages/shared-types` first, then consume in frontend.

### Styling

- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes and CSS variables from `app/globals.css`.
- Keep design tokens centralized; avoid hardcoded hex colors when tokens exist.
- Prefer composition over deeply nested custom CSS.

### Environment Variables

- Only `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` vars are exposed to the browser.
- Never embed backend secrets, database URLs, or API keys in frontend code.

### Error & Loading States

- Every data-fetching page/component must handle loading, empty, and error states.
- Map `ApiClientError.statusCode` to user-friendly messages; don't expose raw stack traces.

## Forbidden Patterns

- Business logic duplication (rating validation, position rules, chemistry calculations).
- Direct database or Prisma access from frontend.
- Importing from `apps/backend/src/` — frontend and backend communicate via HTTP only.
- Inline `fetch` with magic URL strings in page components.
- Storing sensitive tokens in `localStorage` without encryption (when auth is added).
- Using `any` for API response types.
- Client-side-only data fetching when SSR/RSC would work.

## Good Examples

```typescript
// lib/api/client.ts
import type { ApiResponse } from '@draft-io/shared-types';

const API_BASE_URL = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL ?? 'http://localhost:3001/api/v1';

export class ApiClientError extends Error {
  constructor(
    message: string,
    readonly statusCode: number,
  ) {
    super(message);
    this.name = 'ApiClientError';
  }
}

export async function apiGet<T>(path: string): Promise<ApiResponse<T>> {
  const response = await fetch(`${API_BASE_URL}${path}`, {
    headers: { Accept: 'application/json' },
    next: { revalidate: 0 },
  });
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new ApiClientError(`Request failed: ${response.statusText}`, response.status);
  }
  return response.json() as Promise<ApiResponse<T>>;
}
```

```tsx
// app/players/page.tsx — Server Component
import type { PlayerSummary } from '@draft-io/shared-types';
import { apiGet } from '@/lib/api/client';

export default async function PlayersPage() {
  const { data: players } = await apiGet<readonly PlayerSummary[]>('/players');
  return (
    <ul>
      {players.map((player) => (
        <li key={player.id}>{player.displayName}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

## Bad Examples

```tsx
// BAD: inline fetch with duplicated types
export default async function PlayersPage() {
  const res = await fetch('http://localhost:3001/api/v1/players');
  const players: { id: string; name: string }[] = await res.json();
  return <div>{players[0].name}</div>;
}
```

```tsx
// BAD: game rules in frontend
function isValidOverall(rating: number): boolean {
  return Number.isInteger(rating) && rating >= 1 && rating <= 99;
}
```

```tsx
// BAD: importing backend domain
import { Player } from '../../../backend/src/modules/players/domain/entities/player.entity';
```

## Checklist

- [ ] API calls routed through `lib/api/` helpers
- [ ] Types imported from `@draft-io/shared-types`
- [ ] Server Components used unless client interactivity is required
- [ ] Loading, error, and empty states handled
- [ ] No backend source imports or duplicated domain logic
- [ ] Environment variables use `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix for client exposure
- [ ] New API shapes added to shared-types before frontend usage
